article.description: Pau Gasol had a fantastic fourth quarter but could not come up with one more basket.
article.headline: Allen, Radmanovic score 19 apiece
article.linkText: Sonics hold off Grizzlies' late surge for win
article.story: MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- The Seattle SuperSonics held tough. Through almost 10 minutes of the final period, no more than four points, and generally fewer, separated the SuperSonics and the Memphis Grizzlies. And the Grizzlies were out front until the closing minutes. But Seattle ended up with a 97-94 victory, its third win in a row. "We made plays. We made shots down the stretch. We hung in there," said Seattle coach Nate McMillan. Seattle was led by Vladimir Radmanovic and Ray Allen with 19 points each as the SuperSonics held off a late push by the Grizzlies. "Their aggressive play, their guards, basically took our guards out of what we wanted to do offensively," McMillan said. The SuperSonics led by 14 points three times in the second period and held a 56-44 advantage at the half. The Grizzlies staged 14-2 run midway through the final period to take a 78-76 lead on a dunk by Pau Gasol. But Seattle regained the lead for good at 90-88 with 1:33 left on a jumper by Radmanovic. The SuperSonics ended the scoring with two free throws by Antonio Daniels. Gasol tried a desperation 3-pointer with about two seconds left, but the ball bounded off the rim. "They deserve credit. They played great. They made the pressure plays and also made the pressure free throws in the end," said Grizzlies coach Hubie Brown. The Grizzlies had a bad night from the foul line, hitting just 20 of 31 free throws. The SuperSonics hit 21 of 24 from the line. "We stuck together and pulled it out in the end," said Seattle guard Brent Barry, who finished with 13 points. "To come in here and beat this team is tough. The position that they are in, their dominance at home and the fact that they have played great since the break ... It is a big win for us to come in here and grind one out." The Grizzlies are having an outstanding season with 42 victories overall and 11 in the past 13 home games. In their previous best season, the Grizzlies had a total of 28 wins. Rashard Lewis had 12 points for Seattle and Vitaly Potapenko had 11. The Grizzlies were led by Gasol with 21 points and 15 rebounds. James Posey had 13 points for Memphis and Stromile Swift added 12. "We didn't come to play in the first half," said the Grizzlies' Shane Battier. We got down and put ourselves in a hole again." ^Notes: Starting Memphis G Mike Miller remained sidelined with a back injury. Miller left the court Feb. 17 during the Grizzlies' 109-92 victory over Dallas. He took part in non-contact drills Wednesday and may be ready to play Saturday. C Lorenzen Wright remained out with a sprained right knee. ... The game was the final meeting between Memphis and Seattle this season, with Seattle taking a 3-1 lead. Overall, the SuperSonics hold a 30-5 advantage against the Grizzlies ... Memphis G Bonzi Wells was fined $5,000 by the league Thursday for throwing a ball into the stands Tuesday during the Grizzlies' 82-79 victory over Philadelphia.
